did.abstract: This collection include photos, diplomas, invitations, newspapers, early land holdings, 19th century newspaper accounts of the early college, Civil War records, and memorabilia.

prefercite.head: Preferred citation
prefercite.p: University Historical Material records, University Archives, Special Collections Research Center, The George Washington University.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: Materials acquired through transfers from campus offices and gifts from donors.

userestrict.head: Restrictions on Use
userestrict.p: Some material may be copyrighted or restricted. It is the patron's obligation to determine and satisfy copyright or other case restrictions when publishing or otherwise distributing materials found in the collections.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: This collection was created in January 2005 as a way of bringing together a number of small accessions that had never been assigned to a specific record group in The George Washington University Archives. Some of these accessions represent excellent documentation of the early years of the University, both in written and visual form. These include early land holdings, 19th century newspaper accounts of the early college, Civil War records copied form the National Archives, as well as the first student newpapers. Many are surmised to have come from the office of University Historian Elmer Louis Kayser, who was associated with the University as a student and faculty member from 1914-85.

In 2016 and 2017, with the reprocessing of the Office of the President records, some series of photographs and memorabilia were moved into RG0031, and some series and boxes of records from the office of the president were moved into RG0002, resulting in the current series numbering.
Also in 2017, a significant number of artifacts of minimal research value were deaccessioned.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include student records, blueprints, audio tapes, cassette tapes, invitations, speeches, diplomas, newspapers, photographs and negatives, plat maps, academic costumes, scrapbooks, artifacts, charters, and awards. They date from 1821-2012. They were transferred to the University Archives through various campus offices and individuals. Note that not all series have been fully processed. Please contact staff for assistance.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized in 28 series, numbered 1-7 (two series are numbered 2 and two are numbered 6), 9-20, 24, 25, 31, 33, 34, 37, and 53. Photographs are located in series 1, 2, 33, and 34. Early college records are located in series 3. Audio and video recordings are located in series 4 and 20. The remaining series contain former veritcal files, memorabilia, artifacts, newspapers, scrapbooks, awards, and other miscellanea.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: During some clean up work in 2018 the content of box 244 was combined with the content in box 240. Now the collection does not have a box 244.

controlaccess.corpname: Columbian College in the District of Columbia

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs and negatives of individuals, localities, objects, buildings, events, groups associated with the history of The George Washington University. Most are described at the item level but one set of negatives, grouped at the end of the series, is entered at the box level with item-level content information available in a note field. This series also contains paintings, sculptures, drawings, postcards, and other related artwork and images. The material dates from 1859 through the 1990s.

odd.p: Formerly photograph #PA-130 [1852-1924. Ludlow was a graduate student at George Washington University from 1905-1908 while also instructing in "histology and embryology." She is noted as a entomological pioneer. She is buried in Arlington National Cemetary- (taken from her biographical notes at Walter Reed Biosystemics Unit, Smithsonian Institution)]

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Text on image: "Aftab Ahmed of Pakistan received the first degree of Doctor of Public Administration to be conferred by The Geoge Washington University at the annual commencement in the university's 144th year. He earned the degree in the School of Government, Business, and International Affairs. He passed the final oral examination on April 21, 1965, and returned to Pakistan before the commencement so the degree was conferred in absentia. His wife worked in the University Library during her husband's period of study. He holds the degrees of Bachelor of Arts (1943) and Master of Arts (1946) from the University of the Panjab, West Pakistan. Upon his return to Pakistan he expected to head a school for the training of public administrators in Lahore. June, 1965" Formerly photograph #PB-508

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This folder in box 34 contains photographs of the women's rifle team from 1928. Formerly Acc#625.

Elizabeth Clagett "Betty" Clark graduated from The George Washington University with an A.B. degree in 1929. She was a member of the women's rifle team at GW for three years (1927-29), during which time the team won the National Rifle Association national championship each year. Walter Stokes (GW LL.B., 1924, M.D., 1928) a former Olympic (1924) and world champion (1921-24) marksman, served as the coach until 1928, when he resigned following the season. In 1928 Ms. Clark served as manager of the team, and as coach in 1929 and 1930. By then her work as a journalist prevented her from continuing as coach.

Ms. Clark was active in many organizations while a student. These included Kappa Delta, Glee Club, Fencing, President of the Hour Glass, and was a member of the Women's Athletic Association (WAA) Executive Board.
The collection was donated to the University Archives by Betty Clark in 1996.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The materials of this series are a collection of correspondence, member lists, newsletters, speeches, letters, reports, biographical information, addresses, conference transcripts, reports, directories, manuals, newspaper clippings, scrapbook, constitutions, by-laws, notes, chronologies, charters, and resolutions. The material ranges in date from 1819 to 1997.

The material covers the history of GW and includes topics like the Columbian College during the Civil War, the First Baptist Church, the Great Flu epidemic of 1918, and GW during World War II. Correspondence includes that of Presidents Marvin, Trachtenberg, Elliot, and Samson. Other notable individuals mentioned are Chief Justice Warren Burger, Rev. Luther Rice, and University Historian Elmer Louis Kayser.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Five copies of land petitions to Congress requesting that a grant of public lands be made to Columbian College for permanent endowment. These land petitions have the same typed petition letter at the top, however, each document contains different signatures. These signatures are from of various citizens and Columbian College officials. These petitions are from ca. 1820. Formerly Acc 965.

This was transfered to the University Archives by the Dimock Gallery in 2000.
Formerly ACC# 870.

Purchased from Stuart Lutz, Princeton Historic Documents, Inc. in 2000. Formerly ACC# 889.

did.unittitle: Reports of scholarship and deportment of Peter P. Phillips

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Reports from the Collegiate Department in Columbian University and Columbian College concerning scholarship and deportment of Peter Parker Phillips. The reports are signed by Presidents James Welling and George W. Samson. Born October 8, 1852 (died 1931), Peter Parker Phillips began as a student of the Columbian Preparatory School in 1869. He graduated with a B.A. from Columbian University in 1875 (and was a member of the Enosinian Society and Sigma Chi). Mr. Phillips worked at the Naval Observatory and taught at the Preparatory School. He went on to be the rector of St. Paul's Church in Alexandria, Virginia for 26 years. He was the father of Miss Edith Philips, former GW librarian, who donated this collection.
Formerly ACC#952.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This collection was formed in 1988 as an attempt to bring together records of the Columbian College and Columbian University archives (1821-1904).
The Board of Trustees series has been kept as a whole from 1821 to the present, and kept with former Acc#0 (Board of Trustees).

The minutes of the University Council, the President's Council, the Dean's Council, and the Faculty minutes could have been organized in unique series and some material extends past 1904 (actually up to 1928).

The collection is broken down into series contained in manuscript boxes and ledgers, but the original numbering scheme from 1988 has not been been maintained. In 2005 it was re-processed and numbered sequencially.

Records document the early history of faculty, student records, university council, dean's council, treasurer, Enosinian society, National College of Pharmacy, Medical school, Law school, Preparatory school, correspondence, minute books, etc. Formerly ACC#279.

otherfindaid.head: Other Finding Aids
otherfindaid.p: There is a collection related to a court case Colombian College v. Abner W. Clopton's Administrators etc. legal correspondence, 1842-1851 in the Supreme Court of Virginia Archives, Virginia State Law Library.
Also, related to this collection are some digitized materials related to the case.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains awards, medals, certificates, plaques, trophies and diploma. They range in date from 1842 to 1999.

The materials concern the recipients of various awards including Ardeshir Zahedi (Ambassador from Iran), Stephen Trachtenberg, Theo Lorraine Seegrist Donohoe, Charles Wendall Holmes, Jose Abad Santos (for bravery in World War II), Leah Brock McCartney (first female African-Americal to graduate from GW's Law School), Lloyd Elliot, and John Russell Mason (University Librarian and Curator of Art).
The items come from a variety of sources noted at the item level.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Resolution from the Missouri State Senate honoring Leah Brock McCartney (1911-84) for her public service to the state. McCartney is believed to be the first African-American female graduate of the GW Law School. Born Leah Brock in 1911 in Ellisville, Mississippi, she attended Sumner High School in St. Louis, Missouri. Leah subsequently enrolled in Lincoln University in Jefferson City, Missouri, where she received her Bachelor of Science degree in education in 1938. After many years as a teacher, she enrolled in The George Washington University in Washington, D.C., graduating with an LLB degree in 1954. While working full-time, she graduated in three years with the highest grade point average in her third-year class.

Mrs. McCartney became the first female municipal judge of record in Missouri, a distinction for which the Missouri Senate commended her. While serving as municipal judge in Kinloch, Mrs. McCartney commuted between St. Louis and Tulsa, Oklahoma, where she taught law at the University of Tulsa. Of all her achievements, however, Mrs. McCartney was most proud of an award she received from the residents of Kinloch thanking her for the steps she took to improve their community while municipal judge. Another milestone occurred in 1977 when Judge McCartney became the first African-American to serve on the Missouri Public Service Commission. At the time of her death in 1984, Judge McCartney was serving on the board of directors for the Missouri United Methodist Foundation. (From www.leavealegacy.org)

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Alumni Achievement Award of Mrs. Joshua Evans, Jr. (Jessie Fant Evans) "for notable achievement in education and civic service." June 8, 1938. Jesse DuBois Fant Evans was the first woman to serve on George Washington University's Board of Trustees (1924-66). Evans received her A.B. in 1913 (with distinction) and an honorary Doctor of Education in 1932, both from GW. In 1971 Joshua Evans Jr., recognizing his wife's distinguished record and service to the University, established the Jesse Fant Evans Prize. The prize is awarded annually to an outstanding senior student in a contemporary history course. Ms. Evans was also noted for her columns in the Washington Star on the history of Washington, especially the Foggy Bottom area. In 1935 the GW alumni association republished some of those articles for the university. They included "Hamburg: The Colonial Town that Became the Seat of The George Washington University." She received an Alumni Achievement Award in 1938 and a citation from the General Alumni Association in 1954 for "outstanding contributions as an aluma to the development of The George Washington University, the furtherance of its interests and the support of its faculty, students and graduates."

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Diploma of Fabian Franklin, Columbian College. Bachelor of Philosophy, 1869. Latin text. Fabian Franklin (1853-1939) was born in Hungary in 1853, and immigrated with his family to the United States in 1855, settling in Philadelphia, and moving in 1861 to Washington, D.C. He graduated from Columbian College in 1869, and received an honorary Doctor of Laws from Columbian University in 1904. He first trained to become a civil engineer but later entered Johns Hopkins University and earned a Ph.D. in mathematics (1880). He married Christine Ladd in 1882. He remained at Johns Hopkins teaching mathematics from 1879-95, then left to become editor with the Baltimore News, where he remained until 1908. He left to become associate editor of the New York Evening Post. Franklin developed a firm opposition to radical politics and to socialism, in particular. During the First World War he founded a new periodical, called The Review, which merged in 1922 with another paper called The Independent. He wrote a number of books in addition to Plain Talks On Economics. He died suddenly in January of 1939. Formerly ACC#284

odd.head: General
odd.p: Address: 2300 K Street, NW. This three-story Indiana limestone building was known opened September 13th, 1954 as a division of the Hospital, and had two sections, the Warwick Memorial Cancer building and the University Cancer Research building. The building was made possible through the affiliation of the University and the Home for Foundlings, using a sum of about $400,000 left the Home under the will of Randolph T. Warwick, and was named after the donor's sisters. A grant of $200,000 from the National Cancer Institute of the U.S. Public Health Service was used to build the Research section of the structure. In 1926 The Board of Trustees discussed a Warwick bequest for founding a cancer hospital. In 1948 the Board adopted a resolution to approve the contract between the University and the Washington Home for Foundlings concerning a Warwick Cancer Clinic, and in 1950 gave approval to proceed with plans for construction of the building, for which the University donated the land. The Charles H. Tompkins Company built it. In 2012 the Warwick Building was demolished and the new School of Public Health and Health Services building was constructed in its location.

did.unittitle: Academic robe and cap of Charles W. Bliven

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Black academic robe and cap from Charles W. Bliven, who was a Professor of pharmacy from 1940-1963. Also enclosed is a note dated 2-24-97 and reads: " Dear Mr. Anderson, I know that my father would be pleased that his robe will be in the GW archive. I am very pleased for him. Thank you, Sincerely, Virginia Hessels. encl.: Charles W. Bliven's academic robe". These materials were donated in 2000 by Virginia Hessels.

Charles Watson Bliven (1911-xx) was a professor of Pharmacy from 1940-63, and Dean of the Pharmacy School at The George Washington University. The Board of Trustees incorporated the National College of Pharmacy into the University in 1905. The School of Pharmacy remained a part of the University until June 1964 when it was discontinued as a part of an educational reorganization.

Bliven was born in Dakota City, Nebraska November 22, 1911. He received B.S. (1934) and M.S. (1936) degrees from University of Nebraska and was and an instructor of pharmacy there, and a pharmaceutical chemist with the George A. Breon Company before coming to GW in 1940. During World War II, Bliven served in the U.S. Maritime Service and U.S. Navy, leaving with a rank of Lieutenant.

Upon returning from the service, Bliven became Dean of the School of Pharmacy in 1947. He also served as President of the D.C. Pharmaceutical Association in 1953-54 and the American Association of Colleges of Pharmacy in 1959-60. He was awarded an honorary degree from Philadelphia College of Pharmacy and Science in 1960 in recognition of "his outstanding services toward the improvement of pharmaceutical education."
Bliven was a member of Sigma Xi, Phi Lambda Upsilon, and Alpha Sigma Psi. He was married Marjorie Bennett Brew in June 1938, and had two children.
Formerly Acc 816.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

did.unittitle: Cap and gown of Oswald S. Colclough

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Materials in this collection include the cap and gown of Colclough, Dean of the GW Law School (1949-1953) acting GW president (1959-1961, 1964-65). They date from ca.1960, and were donated to the University Archives by Clint Williams in 2001. Oswald Symister Colclough (1898-1981) served twice as acting President of The George Washington University, from 1959-61 and 1964-65. He was also a professor of law and Dean of the Law School from 1949-53, Dean of Facilities from 1953-64 and Provost from 1961-64, retiring from GW in 1964.

Colclough was born in Monroetown, Pennsylvania on November 18, 1898. Following graduation from the U.S. Naval Academy in 1920, he attended GW's Law School and received an LL.B. in 1935, receiving the John Bell Larner Medal for the highest grades in the bachelor of laws program. While at the Naval Academy, Colclough served with the Atlantic Fleet in World War I.

In 1945 he was promoted to rear admiral and in November of that year he was confirmed by the Senate as Judge Advocate General of the Navy. During World War II he commanded submarines for the North Pacific Fleet, later serving as commanding officer of the battleship North Carolina. He retired from active military service in 1950 with the rank of vice admiral.

Admiral Colclough was active in professional and public service roles in the law, defense policy, education and government throughout his academic, legal and military careers. He was a member of the U.S. delegation to the United Nations Conference on Law of the Sea in 1958 and 1960, Chairman of the White House Disarmament Task Force on Navy Inspection, 1955-58, and Director of the Patent, Trademark, and Copyright Research Institute at GW, among other positions. In 1961 GW awarded him an honorary degree as Doctor of Science.
Colclough was married to Kathleen Bain and had three children. He died January 26, 1981 in Chevy Chase, Maryland.
Formerly ACC#1009.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

did.unittitle: Cap and gown of Alexander Wetmore

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Cap and gown of Frank Alexander Wetmore (1886-1978) who was an ornithologist and avian paleontologist, and served as the Smithsonian Institution's sixth Secretary from 1945-1952. Dr. Wetmore was born June 18, 1886 in North Freedom, Wisconsin. After earning his B.S. from the University of Kansas in 1912, he came east. Wetmore received an M.A. in 1916, Ph.D. in 1920, and honorary degree of Doctor of Science in 1932 from The George Washington University.

As a young biologist with the Bureau of Biological Survey of the U.S. Department of Agriculture, Wetmore conducted extensive fieldwork in Latin America. He spent 1911 in Puerto Rico studying bird life, and later traveled through South America for two years investigating bird migration between continents. He was particularly interested in avian anatomy, osteology, fossil birds, migration, and taxonomy. Dr. Wetmore published The Migration of Birds (1926), A Checklist of the Fossil and Prehistoric Birds of North America and the West Indies (1956), and three volumes (1965-72) of an unfinished four-volume work entitled The Birds of the Republic of Panama.

Dr. Wetmore was appointed assistant secretary of the Smithsonian in 1925, where he served for twenty years. Opportunities for field investigations were limited during the Great Depression and World War II. Even so, Wetmore managed to conduct short trips to Haiti, the Dominican Republic, Guatemala, Mexico, Costa Rica, and Colombia. Through his fieldwork, Wetmore established many friendships with Latin American scientists and he strongly encouraged the exchange of specimens and information. He corresponded faithfully with scholars such as Venezuelan botanist Henri Pittier, Brazilian ornithologist Olivario de Pinto, and Brother Apolinar Maria, the Colombian naturalist. Writing to Secretary Charles Greeley Abbot in 1941, Wetmore expressed delight in finally meeting Apolinar in Bogota after decades of correspondence.

Wetmore joined cooperative conservation efforts in Latin America when he was appointed U.S. representative to the Pan American Union's Inter-American Committee of Experts on Nature Protection and Wildlife Preservation in 1940. That year he also served as secretary-general of the Eighth American Scientific Congress. In 1946, as Smithsonian Secretary, Wetmore oversaw the transfer of the Barro Colorado Island research station in Panama to the Smithsonian. Deeply concerned about the conservation of Latin American wildlife, he helped to organize the Pan-American Section of the International Council for Bird Preservation.

In the mid-1940s, Dr. Wetmore began a research program that would occupy his energies for the remainder of his life. Between 1946 and 1966 he traveled to Panama every year to make an exhaustive survey of the birds of the isthmus. This work culminated in the publication of his magnum opus, "The Birds of the Republic of Panama," the last of four volumes was published posthumously in 1984. During his extended stays in remote Indian villages, where the lanky North American was known as "Alejandro Grande," Wetmore learned local customs such as hunting methods. He worked in close association with the scientific community. In 1973, a canopy bridge in the Bayano River Basin in Panama was named in his honor, and he was made an honorary member of many Latin American scientific societies.

Dr. Wetmore donated his enormous natural history collections to the Smithsonian. Included were 26,058 bird and mammal skins from the Americas; 4,363 skeletal and anatomical specimens; and 201 clutches of birds' eggs. Fifty-six new genera, species, and sub-species of birds (both recent and fossil), mammals, amphibians, insects, mollusks, and plants were named in his honor-an assemblage Wetmore called his "private zoo." He was the first to describe 189 species and subspecies of recent birds, mostly from Central and northern South America. An authority on the extinct Pleistocene birds of the West Indies, he had studied fossil avifaunas from Puerto Rico, Haiti, Cuba, and the Bahamas. Avian paleontologist Pierce Brodkorb, when dedicating a newly discovered fossil bird to Wetmore in 1959, stated that he was "responsible for all previous knowledge of fossil birds of the West Indies."

Dr. Wetmore was at one time President of the American Ornithologists Union, Washington Academy of Sciences and Biological Society of Washington. He was also a member of the Cosmos Club of Washington. Dr. Wetmore was given a Distinguished Alumni Achievement Award in 1945 for "service to the University and achievement in science." He served as a Trustee of GW from 1945-64 and as Honorary Trustee from 1964 to his death. He was also president of the General Alumni Association from 1947-50.
Dr. Wetmore was married to Beatrice Wetmore, and had one daughter, Margaret Wetmore Harlan. Dr. Wetmore died Dec. 7, 1978 in Glen Echo, Maryland.
The material was donated to the University Archives by his daughter Margaret Wetmore Harlan in 1998. Dr. Wetmore's papers can be found at the Smithsonian Institution Archives.
Formerly ACC#674
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

Phillips led music for one song for the former and was on the committee of arrangements for the latter. Born October 8, 1852 (died 1931), Peter Parker Phillips began as a student of the Columbian Preparatory School in 1869. He graduated with a BA from Columbian University in 1875 (and was a member of the Enosinian Society and Sigma Chi). Mr. Phillips worked at the Naval Observatory and taught at the Preparatory School.. He went on to be the rector of St. Paul's Church in Alexandria, Virginia for 26 years. He is the father of Miss Edith Philips, former GW librarian, who donated this collection.

Edward Karrick Morris (1897-1981) founded the Federal Storage Company in Washington, and was a long time Trustee of the The George Washington University, serving from 1956-72 (Chairman from 1965-72).

Known as E.K., Mr. Morris was born on January 25, 1897 in New York City. He received his education in Massachusetts at the Berkshire School and later Williams College. After serving in U.S. Naval Aviation in World War I, and then as Director of Athletics at the Berkshire School, he became a resident of Washington, D.C. He married Teresa James in 1924 and in 1925 founded the Federal Storage Company, serving as its president for thirty-eight years, until it merged with the Security Storage Company of Washington in 1963. He was named Chairman of the Board of the consolidated corporation and served until his retirement in 1966. Morris became a Trustee of George Washington University in 1957, was elected Chairman in 1965, and Chairman Emeritus in 1972.

Mr. Morris served as President of the following civic organizations: Washington Executives Association (!940-41); Boy's Clubs of Greater Washington (1948-50); Kiwanis Club of Washington (1952-53); United Givers Fund of the National Capital Area (1956-58); Greater Washington Board of Trade (1959-60); National Capital Area Foundation (1959-60); Boy's Club Foundation (1961-62); Berkshire School General Alumni Association; Williams College Alumni Club of Washington. He was also master of Temple-Noyes Masonic Lodge.

Morris was an Advisory Director of the Riggs National Bank, Director and member of the Executive Committee of the Washington Gas Light Company for eighteen years, Chairman of the Victory Van Corporation for eighteen year, and the Liberty National Bank for twenty years.

Mr. Morris was also a member of the Executive Committee of the Consortium of Universities of Washington, Chairman of the Luther Rice Society at GW, and Chairman of the Executive Committee of the Episcopal Home for Children. For ten years he served as a member of the Board of Governors of St. Albans School, and was a trustee of the Better Business Bureau, Federal City Council, and the National Capital Downtown Committee. He was a Vice President of the Association of Oldest Inhabitants of the District of Columbia, Director of the Young Men's Christian Association of Metropolitan Washington, and member of the Advisory Board of the National Capital Area Council of the Boy Scouts of America. He was also a member of Sigma Phi, Omicron Delta Kappa, Alpha Kappa Psi, and Alpha Phi Omega fraternities.

Mr. Morris received an honorary Doctorate of Laws from Southeastern University in 1956, a Brotherhood Award from the National Conference of Christian and Jews in 1957, Silver Keystone Award of the Boy's Clubs of America in 1970, and an honorary degree of Doctor of Public Service from GW in 1973. In addition to this incredible involvement with the community, E.K. Morris also served as the baseball coach at GW from 1933-42. He died November 20, 1981 in Washington, D.C.

did.unittitle: Autograph book of quotations belonging to book binder and GW faculty member, Marian U. M. Lane

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Born in England, Lane learned the art of book binding and illumination as a young girl and spent two years working in a small studio for Henry James. She later settled in Washington, D.C., working out of her apartment at 1851 Columbia Road. She was an Assistant in Applied Design at The George Washington University from 1907 to 1909. She also gave private lessons out of her home/studio, and practiced the art of bookbinding. Her most famous commissions were books for Queen Elizabeth of Belgium and the Emperor of Japan. Following a heart attack in the mid-1950s, Lane gave up bookbinding, but taught classes in illumination until 1960. She wrote and bound the All Hallows Guild Book for the National Cathedral, and produced Christmas cards for the Cathedral, one of which became a "best seller" with over 300,000 reproductions sold in one year. She was a founding member of the Miniature Painters, Sculptors, and Gravers Society of Washington, D.C.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Unbound book belonging to Marian U. M. Lane (1874-1963) containing a collection of hand-written quotations.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The collection in this series contains newspaper clippings, newsletters, student handbooks, programs, pamphlets, articles, journals, magazines, student newspapers, and university publications. They range in date from 1821 to 2006. This series concerns the history of GW School of Medicine.

Please note that in addition to the Foggy Bottom News issues listed here, there is an additional set (1958-2004) cataloged as part of the Special Collections Research Center's holdings, which can be found by searching the library catalog.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A collection of newspaper clippings concerning George Washington University's women's rifle team. These news clippings from local newspapers concern events and activities of the rifle team. They range in date from 1927-1930. Also included is a letter dated Oct. 26, 1996 from Betty Clark, team manager and coach, to the University Archivist donating these materials.

Elizabeth Clagett "Betty" Clark graduated from The George Washington University with an A.B. degree in 1929. She was a member of the women's rifle team at GW for three years (1927-29), during which time the team won the National Rifle Association national championship each year. Walter Stokes (GW LL.B., 1924, M.D., 1928) a former Olympic (1924) and world champion (1921-24) marksman, served as the coach until 1928, when he resigned following the season. In 1928 Ms. Clark served as manager of the team, and as coach in 1929 and 1930. By then her work as a journalist prevented her from continuing as coach.

Ms. Clark was active in many organizations while a student. These included Kappa Delta, Glee Club, Fencing, President of the Hour Glass, and was a member of the Women's Athletic Association (WAA) Executive Board.
Formerly Acc 625.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

odd.head: General note
odd.p: The "Foggy Bottom News" (1958-2004), the neighborhood newspaper of the area, was donated to the collection as a result of the 1996 exhibit the Foggy Bottom Association and the Gelman Library sponsored called "Fantastic Foggy Bottom: The Growth of a Community." The exhibit was designed in conjunction with GW's 175th Anniversary, and a committee was formed to collect and choose materials for inclusion in the exhibit. The newspaper documents to a high degree the interaction of the community with The George Washington University, which moved to the Foggy Bottom area in 1912. Generally, it was published monthly. Ellie Becker was the editor of the paper from 1989-2004, when publication ceased. It was revived in December 2005 by its new editor, Michael Malloy. This set of publications range in date from February 1958 to October 1973. They were donated to the University Archives in 2004 by the editor of the paper, Ellie Becker. Formerly Acc 553.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Materials in this collection include football programs belonging to William Helvestine. They range in date from 1930-35, and were donated to the University Archives by Joan C. Netherwood in January 2005.

William Helvestine lived in Washington, D.C. and graduated from The George Washington University with an LL.B. degree in 1935. While a student at GW he was a member of Acacia, Omicron Delta Kappa (President 1934-35), Gate and Key (Secretary 1932-33, President 1933-34), Interfraternity Council 1931-33 (Vice President 1932-33), Student Council 1933-35 (President 1933-34). He was also a member of the football team (freshman in 1929 and varsity in 1930). Upon graduation he worked for the Treasury Department.
Acc#2005.002; formerly MS2000

He was also a member of the football team (freshman in 1929 and varsity in 1930). Upon graduation he worked for the Treasury Department.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series comprises casette tape audio recordings that were previously included in the Oral History Collection, but are not, in fact, oral histories. It includes recordings of speeches, musical events and groups including the GW Glee Club and the Troubadors, and radio programs featuring GW presidents and others.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This cassettes in this series are not arranged in any particular order.

phystech.head: Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
phystech.p: This collection contains audio recordings that are currently only stored on cassette. Researchers who wish to access these recordings may be required to pay for their digitization, and will be provided with access to the digitized version. Please contact the Public Services Coordinator and Outreach Librarian at speccoll@gwu.edu for additional information about this process.

did.unittitle: Act passed by Legislative Assembly of the District of Columbia, July 25, 1871

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: This act amended the original University Charter to permit the Columbian College to apply the proceeds from any sale of its property to pay off existing indebtedness and to put its property and equipment in good condition. The act also modified the Charter to achieve administrative efficiency. To replace the existing Board of Trustees, the act created a corporation of the College, consisting of 13 Trustees, residents of the District of Columbia, and 13 Overseers. The president of the Corporation and its secretary-treasurer were to be selected from the Trustees. The act specified the meeting schedule of the Corporation, the Trustees, and the Board of Overseers. The act also stated that while no real estate or other property could be sold by the Trustees without the vote of the Corporation, other routine matters could be handled by the Trustees. The President of the United States, the Chief Justice of the United States, the Attorney General, the Governor of the District of Columbia, and the Delegate of the District of Columbia were made honorary members of the Corporation, without vote.

did.unittitle: Memoranda of Points of Agreement for an Organic Relation Between the Columbian University and its Medical Department and Dental School, November 24, 1897

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: In 1898 the Medical and Dental Schools were brought within the financial structure of the University, and the Medical building was turned over to the University.

did.unittitle: Ordinance Creating the School of Jurisprudence and Diplomacy, circa October 12, 1898

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: This ordinance, prepared and presented by Board of Trustees member, Charles Willis Needham, established a School of Comparative Jurisprudence and Diplomacy which provided for a master's degree in law and/or a degree in diplomacy from the George Washington University.

did.unittitle: Two Certified Copies of the Articles of Incorporation of the Columbian College, and Recorder's Receipts

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: This Charter changed the name of Columbian University to the George Washington University. It also established the Columbian College as the body controlling all academic undergraduate institutions within the University.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Under the provisions of the March 3, 1905 supplemental Act of Congress amending the charter of The George Washington University, this established the Washington College of Engineering, a semi-independent undergraduate college of the University.

did.unittitle: Signed Board of Trustees Resolution (May 6, 1909), and Recorder's Receipts for Certificate of Corporation Seal (1908) and Certificate of Increase of Membership (1909)

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: This resolution by the George Washington University Board of Trustees increased the number of Trustees and authorized GW alumni to nominate each year two from their number to serve three-year terms as Trustees.

bioghist.p: The National College of Pharmacy was taken over by the George Washington University as an affiliated college.
